        <h1 class="orange">Cyclist skills & rules to follow</h1>
        <h3 class="green">Cyclist skills training</h3>                    
        <p class="beta-p">Learning to ride a bicycle takes lots of practice so you should consider taking a course. Courses vary and cover a range of skills depending on who they are designed for. If you are interested in taking a course, contact your local council, bike club or bike shop to find a local training provider. </p>
        <p class="beta-p">The NZ Transport Agency <a href="http://www.nzta.govt.nz/resources/roadcode/cyclist-code/about-cycling/cyclist-skills-training.html" style="text-decoration:none" target="_blank"><i>(NZTA)</i></a> , Bike NZ and CAN have recently developed national guidelines for cyclist skills training.</p>
        <h3 class="green">Rules</h3>                                                  
        <p class="beta-p">Before cycling on the road you must know the road rules. They apply to cyclists as well as those using motor vehicles. The rules help to prevent crashes and reduce risk of injury.</p>
        <p class="beta-p">Always ride as near as you can to the left side of the road. If you are holding back traffic you must move as far as possible to the left side of the road to allow traffic to pass, as soon as you can. However, you do need to cycle in a sensible position on the road to keep safe.</p> 
        <p class="beta-p">Two cyclists can ride next to each other but should take into account the keep left rule and not hold back traffic. Three or more people cycling next to each other is illegal, except in the case of a road race that has been given traffic management approval from a road controlling authority.</p>
        <p class="beta-p">Use hand signals to show other road users what you are doing.</p>
        <p class="beta-p">You must obey all signs and signals.</p>
        <p class="beta-p"><strong>You can learn lots more safety rules for cycles at <a href="http://www.nzta.govt.nz/resources/roadcode/cyclist-code/about-cycling/rules.html" style="text-decoration:none" target="_blank"><i>(NZTA-rules-for-cycles).</i></a></strong></p>
        <hr>
      </div>
